ce:section.ce:para:
In this study, we present a planar waveguide that selectively harvests near UV light, and demonstrates its coupling with PDLC window device to modulate the transmission of visible and near-IR light. Schematic representation of solar spectrum management using our proposed system is shown in Fig. 1
                     . Waveguide coupled PDLC device with the final dimension of 50 mm × 25 mm × 4.2 mm is prepared by integrating the nitrogen-doped carbon quantum dots (N-CQDs) based waveguide with PDLC cell such that PDLC in OFF state acts as a backside scatterer. The dimension of the prepared device is N-CQDs absorb the near UV light (300–400 nm) and re-emit the light (390–590 nm) that is trapped inside a waveguide and moved towards its edges from where it is collected by the attached solar cell for electric power generation (Fig. 2
                     ). PDLC, besides regulating the incoming light upon switching, reflects the untrapped light back into waveguide during its OFF state. It also redirects a portion of incoming light that is not absorbed (i.e. outside the absorption range of the N-CQDs) towards the edges. N-CQDs belongs to a novel class of non-toxic semiconducting materials and their synthesis involves a simple solvothermal approach which is extremely cost competitive (Rigodanza, 2018; Ding, 2018; Kundu, 2018). Moreover, they offer a significant advantage over organic dyes due to their inherently tunable absorption band and long-term photo stability which is paramount for the successful realization of energy generating window. To the best of our knowledge, proposed management of photons using PDLC smart window and specifically the use of N-CQDs for imparting the energy generating feature to such window has not been explored previously.
